## Scoring Summary

| **Framework** | **Safety** | **Performance** | **DX** | **Ecosystem** | **Total** | **Best For** |
|---------------|------------|-----------------|--------|---------------|-----------|--------------|
| **Azumi** | ğŸ† 9.5/10 | ğŸ¥‡ 9/10 | 6/10 | 4/10 | 7.1/10 | **Type-safe SSR** |
| **Leptos** | 8/10 | 7/10 | 6.5/10 | 6/10 | 6.9/10 | **Rust React alternative** |
| **Dioxus** | 8/10 | 6.5/10 | 6.5/10 | 6.5/10 | 6.9/10 | **Cross-platform apps** |
| **Maud** | 8/10 | 9.5/10 | 7.5/10 | 4.5/10 | 7.4/10 | **Content-heavy sites** |
| **Templ** | 8/10 | 9.5/10 | 8/10 | 5/10 | 7.6/10 | **Go-based web apps** |
| **Next.js** | 6/10 | 7/10 | 8.5/10 | 9.5/10 | 7.8/10 | **Full-stack JavaScript** |
| **Svelte** | 7.5/10 | 8.5/10 | 8.5/10 | 8/10 | 8.1/10 | **Performance + simplicity** |

## Key Insights

### ğŸ† **Winners by Category**

**Compile-Time Safety**: Azumi (only framework that validates both HTML and CSS)
**Performance**: Maud/Templ (zero runtime), Azumi (server-first)
**Developer Experience**: Next.js/Svelte (mature ecosystems)
**Ecosystem**: Next.js (massive), Svelte (growing fast)
**Learning Curve**: Svelte (easiest), Templ (simple Go templates)
**Production Ready**: Next.js (proven at scale), Svelte (proven)

### ğŸ“Š **Technology Adoption Timeline**

```
2020: Maud, Svelte mature
2021: Dioxus launches
2022: Leptos launches  
2023: Azumi, Templ launch
2024: All frameworks stable
2025: Azumi Live features complete (projected)
```

### ğŸ¯ **Decision Matrix**

**Choose Azumi if**: You want maximum compile-time safety and have Rust expertise
**Choose Next.js if**: You need ecosystem support and rapid development
**Choose Svelte if**: You want performance without complexity
**Choose Leptos/Dioxus if**: You prefer React patterns but want Rust performance
**Choose Maud/Templ if**: You need template-heavy sites with your backend language

